# =============================================================
# Trivy Ignore File
# =============================================================
# WHY? Some vulnerabilities are in the Node.js base image's
# BUNDLED global npm (/usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/) — NOT our app code.
# These packages are only used by npm CLI itself (not at runtime by our app).
#
# WHAT WE'RE IGNORING AND WHY:
#   picomatch CVEs — in node:22-alpine's bundled npm internals.
#     Our app does NOT use picomatch at runtime (only jest uses it for testing).
#     The production image runs 'node src/server.js' — npm is never invoked.
#
#   brace-expansion CVE — same: bundled in npm CLI, not used by our app at runtime.
#
# These are ACCEPTED RISKS because:
#   1. The attack vector requires the attacker to control a file glob pattern
#      passed to our app — which our API does not expose.
#   2. npm is never called at runtime inside the container.
#   3. We are monitoring for fixed versions and will remove these ignores
#      when node:22-alpine ships a patched npm version.
# =============================================================

# HIGH: picomatch - ReDoS via crafted extglob patterns
# Location: /usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/picomatch/
# Why acceptable: npm is never invoked at container runtime; only 'node src/server.js' runs.
CVE-2026-33671

# MEDIUM: picomatch - Data integrity via POSIX bracket expression injection
# Same location and rationale as above.
CVE-2026-33672

# MEDIUM: brace-expansion - DoS via zero step value
# Location: /usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/brace-expansion/
# Same rationale: brace-expansion is only used by npm CLI, not at runtime.
CVE-2026-33750
